{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_ivy_ver01/data/sn83004278/00340581982/1958010201/0003.xml":{"full_text":"VL StJneu Merald\nc. R. HURL1\nEditor and Publisher\nOFFICIAL NEWSPAPER OP\nRICHLAND COUNTY. MONTANA\nNATIONAL EDITORIAL\ns S> c 5'8\nN\nRliMI O*\nCiATl\u00bbW\naltered at the Poetafflce at Sidney.\nMontana, as Second Class Matter March\n13. 1MB. under the Act of Mach 3. 2878.\nPublished every Thursday at Sidney,\nRichland County, Montana.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nRkhland-MoKenzle Counties. $3 00\nyear; $3-60 a year In Montana: $4.00\nyear outside Mot tana. Single copies 10c,\nForeign Countries $5.50.\nEDITORIALLY\n\"COURAGE MO\u00dcNTETH\nWITH OCCASION\"\nMore than tnree hundred years\nago the great Francis Bacon\nwrote: \"The virtue of prosperity\nis temperance; the virtue of ad\nversity is fortiude; which in\nmorals is the more heroical vir\ntue.\"\nA few weeks ago the Vice Pres\nident of the United States held a\npress conference, directly follow\ning the failure of this country's\nfirst attempt at launching an earth\nsatellite. Mr. Nixon said: \"Sure\nwe failed. We have before and\nwe will again. But we need to\nkeep our sense of proportion- We\nhaven't overnight lost our scien\ntific know-how, our ability to\nget things done. Let's get away\nfrom our weeping walls and act\nlike Americans. We've got work\nto do. Let's get on with it like\nAmericans.\"\nThere is a great gulf of time\nand language between these two\nquotations. But both of them stem\nfrom the same attitude\nsame outlook on life and the de\nmands of life.\nSome Americans met the Rus\nsian scientific successes in ostrich\nstyle by trying to ignore them\nor by deprecating them. Some, at\nthe other extreme, reacted with\npanic and despair an all-is\nlost attitude- They showed them\nselves lacking in \"the virtue of\nadversity of which Francis Ba\ncon wrote. Or they went to the\n\"weeping walls\" of which Rich\nard Nixon spoke.\nBut these people were very\nmuch in the minority. The great\nmajority of Americans fully un\nderstand that there is work to do\nand we must get on with it.\nThe problem, then, is how to\ndo it\nRussia has been showing the\nworld some of the fruits of a\nharsh materialistic system. Her\nachievements and only a fool\nwill now try to minimize them\u2014\nhave been brought about by\nforce. The abilities of people are\nthe\nARN\u00cfE HAUGEN\nELECTRIC SHAVERS\nSALES and SERVICE\nSmall AppUaaee Repair\nFreMtes'e Oarage\nOr lit ted An. N.W.\nGat Lump or Stoker\nCOAL\nmi the\nTHIEL COAL MINE\nPkone 187 P.O. Box 58S\nOpen Every Day\nj\n\n\nI\nj\nI\nj\nI\n\nr\nV\n\nHi MS MS MHOS mi\nI\nWhen you have too many things to do, you\nsave time by making your bank deposits with us\nthe easy way. Simply fill in a mail deposit form,\nenclose your deposit, stamp your envelope-and\nlet the postman do the rest. Get free forms now.\ncan\nBBff/t By MBtt\nTT\n\nTT\nT\nI\nVII\nk\n\u00a337*\nj\n\n\u00c0mtL\nr\u00fcl\nICE CORPORATION\n'MEMBER. FEDERAL DEPOSIT I N$UI\ncarefully, efficiently and rigorous\nly channeled into whatever ave\nnues best serve the purposes of\nthe state. The rewards for suc\ncess are often very great; the\npenalties for failure are often\nextremely severe. In any event,\nthe individual has small com\nmand over his own destinies' The\nstate makes the important deci\nsions and provides the directions.\nCan a free people rival and\nsurpass the achievements of such\na system and still keep their\nfreedom, their traditions, and\ntheir national heart and soul?\nHistory tells us that we can.\nTime and time again the forces\nof freedom have defeated the\nforces of tyranny.\nBut the exact opposite also has\noccurred. Great civilizations have\nfallen to barbarian hordes. This\nhas happened when those civili\nzations grew soft and sleek, con\ntented and slack, immersed in\nluxury and degenerate in charac\nter. It has happened when faith\nwas lost in principles and insti\ntutions that led to greatness\nto be replaced by overwhelming\ncynicism. It has happened, in sum,\nwhen fortitude did not come out\nof adversity, when defeatism pre\nvailed, and citizens turned to the\n\"weeping walls'.'\nWe do not yet know the ex\ntent of the efforts that will be\nneeded to build and to maintain\nthe strengh necessary for survi\nval. But we do know that they\nwill be great, and future events\nmay demonstrate that they will\nbe greater than anyone realizes\nnow. The burden will fall upon\nall on industry, labor, govern\nment. Restraint and wisdom will\nbe needed by all the national\ninterest must come ahead of self\ninterest. But no one should look\non this burden with distaste or\nfear. The times have brought\nchallenge and opportunity and\na people which value freedom and\nhonor will rise voluntarily and in\nfull willingness to meet the chal\nlenge and exploit the opportunity.\nHere another thing that was\nsaid many centuries ago is per\nfectly in keeping. Shakespeare\nput it into the mouth of one of\nhis characters: \"Courage moun\nteth with occasion.\" The occasion\nis at hand. We must now prove\nour courage. \u2014Industrial News\nReview.\nFARM FIGHT\nCERTAIN AGAIN\nA farm fight is once again cer\ntain in Congress, thanks partly\nto the unusually large wheat crop\nwhich has been officially predict\ned.\nOnce again the efforts of\nSecretary of Agriculture Ezra Taft\nBenson, to hold down production\nof a vital farm crop, have failed.\nThe wheat yield this year is ex\npected to be 20.6 bushels high\nest yield on record.\nThe crop is expected to total\n906,272,000 bushels. Such a crop\nnaturally seriously threatens to\ncomplicate the already serious\nfarm problem facing the nation,\nespecially the problem concern\ning surpluses.\nBenson has announced he will\nhave many farm legislation rec\nommendations ready for the sec\nond session of the 85 th Congress.\nBut the chairman of the House\nAgriculture Committee, Democrat\nHarold Cooley (NC) says they\nwill be junked.\nCooley and a surprising num\nber of Rfepublicans, feel that Ben\nson's approach to the surplus\nproblem is all wet. More and\nmore legislators want a two-price\nstructure for several of the coun\ntry's farm products. The best fea\nture of the plan, and there are\nseveral good features to it, is\nthat a farmer would be given\nprice support for a certain quan\ntity of a certain crop.\nHe could plant as much as he\nTed Nelson\nSIDNEY MUSIC MART\nInstructor ia piano, accordion,\nviolin, guitar and mandolin\nPHONE 472R\n17-tfc\nliked, but all raised over this\nquantity would have to be sold\non the free market\nworld market. That would main\ntain the support price for our\nfarmers and enable some to make\na profit on the free market with\nan additional crop.\nIt would also enable manu\nfacturers to buy farm goods and\nproducts (such as cotton) more\ncheaply and be able to compete\nbetter with foreign producers.\nIf Benson does not get what he\nwants, it would seem wise for the\nAdministration to try Congress'\nsuggestions this time.\nperhaps the\nPOWERING A\nREVOLUTION\nThe President of the Farm\nEquipment Institute recently said\nthat, on the basis of available\nfigures, sales of tractors and other\nfarm machinery will be better this\nyear than last. He mentioned two\ncausative factors concerned. For\none thing, farm income generally\nhas run at higher levels than in\n1956. For another, to quote him\ndirectly, farmers want to obtain\nmore modern farm equip\nment to help offset rising costs\nof farm labor, and to improve\ntheir income.\"\nHe added: \"The trend towards\nlarger acreage on family-type\nfarms and the use of modern\nfarm equipment adapted to that\ntype of an operation, which make\nfor increased savings and time\nliness in performing farm work,\nwill continue in the immediate\nyears ahead.\"\nThis is of special interest when\nread in conjunction with a Farm\nJournal editorial. That magazine\nsays; \"The rural scene in Ameri\nca is undergoing phenomenal\nchanges these days.\" For instance,\nour farmers are producing food\nand fiber for a soaring popula\ntion\u2014yet the farm population\nsteadily declines. Last April, for\ninstance, there were 4,700,000\nfewer farmers than in 1950. And\nmore than 2 million farm people\nwork regularly at other jobs.\nFarm equipment is largely re\nsponsible for this phenomena. It\nhas given every farm worker a\nproductive power that would\nseem unbelievable to the farmers\nof other generations. It has re\nduced costs, increased efficiency,\nand taken much of the drudgery\nout of farm tasks. The machine\npowered, and continues to power,\nthe agricultural revolution.\nTHE JANUARY SKY\nThe winter skies in January\noften clear and cold, offer star\ngazers beautiful nights for the\nstudy of the stars and planets.\nThe Big Dipper is still far\ndown on the horizon, but it is\nbeginning to move back up into\nthe sky. Morning stars (actually\nplanets of the solar system visible\nto the naked eye) will be Mer\ncury, Mars, Jupiter and Saturn.\nThat bright evening star (plan\net) will be Venus.\nWhy not make it one of your\n1958 resolutions to buy a guide\non the stars and study them\nonce in a while during the com\ning year? We are fast approach\ning the space age and, even more\nimportant, you will find the study\nimmensely rewarding and stimu\nlating.\nIt may not be too many years\nbefore people will be visiting the\nplanets you study today, thinking\nthey are so remote and unreach\nable!\nRemember...\nEarly Day Sidney News Briefs\nMrs. Aitbar Nelson\nHelena, Montana\nMesdames E. B. Brown, David\nHardy and Miss Josephine Stout\nwere hostesses at a very delight\nful Kensington last Thursday af\nternoon at a guessing game. The\nprize was won by Mrs. Norman\nWebster and Mrs. W. F. P\u00e9ters.\nThe hostesses served a delicious\nlunch at the close of the after\nnoon.\nNov. 1. 1928\n\nRichland Post No. 12, American\nLegion of Sidney held its annual\nelection of officers on Armistice\nDay. Keith Carpenter was elect\ned Commander of the Post. Paul\nB. Hurd, Vice Commander; J. M.\nLexcen, Adjutant; Lyle Bell, Fi\nnance Officer; F. J. Matoushek,\nHistorian; Wm. Seitz, Chaplain;\nLloyd Tewes, Sergeant at Arms;\nExecutive Committee\u2014Herb Kin\ncaid, H. F. DePue, Roy Rounce,\nGuy Severson and Harry Clark..\nNov. 15. 1928\n\nMr. and Mrs. Arcade Simard\nare the hosts at a large gathering\nof friends at a Thanksgiving din\nner today at their country home\nnorthwest of town. The guests will\ninclude Ed Dore and family. Job\nDore and family and Ted O'Brien\nand family.\nNov. 29, 1928\n\nJohnny Cattaneo and Albino\nZoanni of the Andes community\nleft last week for a trip to Italy\nand Switzerland. They will be\ngone several months. Milo Her\nbert is looking after Mr. Cat\ntaneo's ranch during his absence.\nNov. 29, 1928\n\nQuite a bunch of boy friends\nof Bruce Johnson were enter\ntained at a six o'clock dinner Sat\nurday evening at the Johnson\nhome in honor of Bruce's ninth\nbirthday. After dinner the boys\nwent to see Uncle Tom's Cabin\nat the Princess.\nNov. 29, 1928\nMany of the families from our\ncommunity enjoyed and partici\npated in the grade school Christ\nmas program held Tuesday eve\nning.\nOptimistic\nOutlook For\nIke New Year\nWESTERN STATES FAVORED\nIN GENERAL PROSPECT\nWestern industrialists look at\n1958 a little more optimistically\nthan those in other sections of\nthe U. S., according to a coast-to\ncoast survey conducted by the Na\ntional Association of Manufactur\ners.\nThe West's optimistic edge was\nnoted by William Bynum of Syr\nacuse, N. Y., in making survey\ndata public during NAM's 62nd\nannual Congress of American In\ndustry in New York, Dec. 4-6.\nBynum, president of Carrier\nCorp., addressed delegates on \"A\nReport on American Business.\"\nBasis for the difference is the\nWest's anticipated greater popu\nlation growth, however, Bynum\nexplained. Westerners agree with\ntheir counterparts elsewhere that\ntaxation is the major factor re\nstricting future business expan\nsion.\n4,300\na\nfor\nWesterners represent 16 per\ncent of the more than\nAmerican industrialists polled by\nNAM in efforts to determine the\nnation's business outlook for. '58.\nNearly 700 businessmen in the\n11 Western states answered six\nkey questions.\nSteady growth in 1958 through\ncapital outlays is expected by\n57 per cent of Westerners\nfeeling shared by only 55 per\ncent of all American industrial\nists polled. Of the balance, pes\nsimism shades optimism among\nboth Western and all other poll\nparticipants.\nSales outlook also is viewed\nmore favorably by Westerners.\nIncreased sales volumes are an\nticipated by 30 per cent, com\npared to 36 per cent nationwide.\nExpecting a status quo situation\nin sales are 42 per cent of West\nerners and 45 per cent of busi\nnessmen elsewhere. A pessimistic\nnote is sounded by 19 per cent\nin both categories.\nMore Westerners than other\nU. S. businessmen, percentage\nwise, expect th\u00e7 dollar profit\ntrend to remain at or climb ahead\nof 1957 levels. And, it follows,\nfewer Westerners foresee a dollar\nprofit slump.\nAll industrialists polled see\npopulation growth and expanding\nmarkets as the major economic\nforces calling for expansion. Half\nof Westerners list population\nfirst, however, as against a na\ntional rating of 37 per cent.\nOther economic growth factors\nrated just under population and\nmarkets are competition, new\nproducts and defense require\nments. Westerners stress defense\nactivity a shade more, however,\nand both groups list consumer\nspending and export demand last.\nTaxation burdens not only are\nlisted by both groups as the ma\njor unfavorable economic force\nlikely to restrict expansion in\n1958, but also are labeled as the\ngreatest problem facing American\nbusiness.\nThis mutually held opinion ac\ncounts, in large measure,\ngrowing support among both big\nand small businessmen of tax re\nlief as embodied in the biparti\nsan rate reduction plan proposed\nby U. S. Reps. A. N. Sadlak\n(R. Conn.) and A. S. Herlong\n(D. Fla.).\nUnion demands rate fifth be\nhind costs, business uncertainty\nand tight credit as other expan\nsion barriers, but problems at\ntendant to labor are listed second\nonly to taxation as the business\nworld's greatest concern in 1958.\nTaxation and labor, in fact,\ndraw more than half of both\nWesterners' and other U. S. in\ndustrialists' votes as the greatest\nproblems facing business today.\nPublisher Tom Anderson of\nFarm and Ranch quips: \"The Rus\nsians may beat us to the moon\nwith a Sputnik But I'll bet we\nget there first with Foreign Aid.\"\nAn article by F. A. Harper in\nThe Freeman says that federal\ngrants to the states this year will\namount to about $80 per family\nas against $30 per family 10\nyears ago.\nYellowstone\nTownship\nMrs. Peter Heinle\nA happy and Blessed New Year\nto all of our readers.\nProsperous Valley Farmers\nUnion will meet Friday, evening\nJanuary 3 at the school for class\nes and a program. Bring buns or\ncookies for lunch. Plans are to\nserve \"slushburgers.\"\nMr. and Mrs. Elmer Liebelt\nof Circle spent the holidays with\nrelatives here and were among\nthe guests at a dinner at the home\nof Mr. and Mrs. Albert Liebelt\non Christmas Day.\nMr. and Mrs. John Hutter en\ntertained at a Christmas Day din\nner, Mr. and Mrs. William Se\nverance and Keith an d Mr. and\nMrs. Ludwig Hutter.\nSeveral ladies called on Mrs.\nBill Moore on Saturday afternoon\nand helped her celebrate her\nbirthday with a lunch and gifts.\nMrs. Peter Heinle baked a birth\nday cake.\nMr. and Mrs. Thomas Biehl\nand Karen are leaving Thursday\nfor Billings, where Karen will\nundergo surgery on her arm,\nwhich was broken a number of\nyears ago and has not healed\nproperly. She will be confined to\na hospital there for a week.\nEarl Nice made a trip to Bil\nlings last week by plane for\nmedical check-up.\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Schoen\nberger left Sunday morning for\nMinneapolis, where they will\nspend a few days. We under\nstand that while there they also\nmarketed their furs the result\nof this winter's trapping.\nDonna Heinle spent Friday\nwith Betty Ann Johnson at\nCartwright and remained over\nfor the evening reception for the\nLasseys at the hall.\nA holiday dinner was held at\nthe home of Mr. and Mrs. Bill\nMoore Sunday with relatives\nfrom Glendive, Mr. and Mrs.\nH. E. Dickey; Mr. and Mrs. John\nKnoll and girls and Mr. and Mrs.\nArt Anvik and family in attend\nance and Alva Danielson, Wat\nford City.\nMrs. Viola Taasevigen arrived\nhome this week from Tacoma and\nSpokane where she has been vis\niting over the holidays.\nMrs. Phyllis Gardner, Billings,\nspent a few days here at the\nhome of her parents, Mr. and\nMrs. Tony Pominville.\nMr. and Mrs. A. W. Morrill\nand Mr. and Mrs. Gerald Morrill\nentertained at a family dinner at\nthe Morrill home Christmas Day\nwith Mr. and Mrs. Don Morrill,\nWilliston, Mr. and Mrs. Frank\nN\u00e4rrin and family, New Town;\nMr. and Mrs. Dale Dean and\nfamily, Cartwright; Carl Hun\nter, Mr. and Mrs. George Hunter\nand family and Mrs. and Mrs.\nCurtis Hunter and family as\nguests.\nMr. and Mrs. Albert Liebelt,\nMr. and Mrs. Richard Hayden\nand Mr. and Mrs. Jerry Olson\nwere Williston shoppers Friday.\nMr. and Mrs. Jerry Lewis and\nfamily were over from Watford\nCity on Christmas and were din\nner guests at the home of his\nparents Mr. and Mrs. George\nLewis.\nMr. and Mrs. Peter Heinle and\nfamily and Mrs. Alda Welsch\nwere supper guests at the James\nSanderson home New Year's Eve.\nAudrey Noteboom, Waftord\nCity, spent several days here this\nweek at the home of her parents,\nthe Paul Notebooms. She return\ned home Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Jerry Olson who\nhave spent the holidays here\nwith her parents the Richard\nHaydens, went to Dickinson Mon\nday, where Jerry was to under\ngo surgery to remove a pin from\nthis arm which had been placed\nthere a year ago when he broke\nhis shoulder in an accident while\nattending Dickinson Teacher's Col\nlege.\nMr. and Mrs. Herman Johnson\nand Mr. and Mrs. J. Stubbs at\ntended funeral services at Willis\nton Saturday morning for Miss\nEsther Jack, one of the first\nwhite children to be born in\nWilliams county. She was well\nknown by many local people as\nshe had been very active in vari\nous organizations, all of her life\nand was a graduate from the\nengineering department of the\nUniversity of North Dakota.\nMr. and Mrs. Clifford Stubbs,\nMinot, spent a few days here at\nthe Jack Stubbs and Herman\nJohnson homes.\nJanis Dschaak was guest of\nhonor at a party on her birthday\ngiven by a group of young people\nat the home of Bonnie and Bev\nerly Hayden Thursday evening.\nMrs. John Halmot, Livingston,\nhas been here visiting her par\nents, the Louis Stepan, Srs., and\nher brother and family, the Louis\nStepan, Jrs.\nMark Worst, son of Mr. and\nMrs. Clayton Worst Jr., was ill\nlast week with pneumonia but is\nquite himself again.\nPvts. Dennis Noteboom, Marvin\nSkogen and Robert Miller left\nNew Year's to return to Ft. Ord,\nCalifornia, where they are sta\ntioned.\nSioux Pass\nBy Homemaker\u00bb' Club\nChristmas Day dinner guests at\nthe Charlie Hackley home were\nMr. and Mrs. Clifford McGinnis\nand girls Mr. and Mrs. Leo Hack\nley and family, Mr. and Mrs.\nCharlie Clemmer and Patsy, Mr.\nand Mrs. EcUClemmer and Deb\nbie, Mr. and Mrs. LeRoy Larsen\nand boys. Afternoon callers were\nMr. and Mrs. Charles McGinnis\nand family.\nMr. and Mrs. Bob Johnson and\nboys spent Christmas day with\nMrs. Johnson's parents, Mr. and\nMrs. Harry Hill of Nashua.\nCasper Wick and Dennie were\nWednesday morning coffee guests\nat the Charles McGinnis home.\nMr. and Mrs. Casper Wick and\nfamily\nguests at the home of her moth\ner, Mrs. Elva Putnam.\nChristmas eve supper guests at\nthe Clifford McGinnis home were\nMr. and Mrs. Charles McGinnis\nand family, Mr. and Mrs. Arvon\nSalvevold and family, Mr. and\nMrs. Don Jensen and family and\nMr. and Mrs. LeRoy Larsen and\nboys and Mr. and Mrs. Ernest\nMcGinnis.\nCasper Wick, Ronnie and Den\nnie were Friday dinner guests at\nTuesday dinner\nwere\nKIRBY CO. of SIDNEY\nKIRBY VACUUM CLEANERS\nSales and Service\nFREE Demonttration\nRepretentali re*\nCHRIS GAUB ^90\nPhone 1049-W\nHT BOB WAGNER XO\n302 No. Central Phone 303-J\nthe Ervin Putnam home. Janet\nKay was on the sick list so she\ncouldn't go.\nMr. and Mrs. Charles McGin\nnis and family were Thursday af\nternoon visite at the home of\nher mother, Mrs. Marene Oel\nkers in Culbertson.\nThe St. Peter's church of this\narea had their Sunday school\nprogram Thursday morning. Rev.\nTande was a dinner guest at the\nhome of Mr. and Mrs. Casper\nWick that day.\nMr. and Mrs. Frank Bailey and\nfamily, and Rodney Mason spent\nChristmas Day at the John Forbes\nhome near Bainville. While there\nthey also visited with Mrs. Bail\ney's uncle, Nick Skorick, and also\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Skorick of\nButte, N. D., whom she had\nnever met.\nThursday evening visitors at\nthe Charles McGinnis home were\nMr. and Mrs. Clifford McGinnis,\nMr. and Mrs. Raymond Norby\nand family.\nChristmas Day dinner guests at\nthe Casper Wick's were Mr. and\nMrs. Roy Brose and family of\nSavage, Mr. and Mrs. Jim Put\nnam and family, and Dick Gold\nsmith.\nJohn Koozenney was a Friday\nmorning coffee guest at the Frank\nBailey home.\nMr. and Mrs. Charles McGinnis\nand family were among the 35\nguests Friday night at a supper\nat the Howard Iversen home at\nCulbertson.\nMr. and Mrs. Casper Wick and\nfamily were Tuesday afternoon\ncoffee guests at the Art Sorte\nberg home at Fairview.\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Anvik spent\nChristmas day at her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. Philip Schl\u00e4gel at\nFroid.\nMr. and Mrs. Charles McGinnis\nand family, Mr. and Mrs. LeRoy\nLarsen, and boys, Mr. and Mrs.\nMONEY AND BANKING\nIn Everyday Living\nwatch TV (electric), Mother\nlistens to radio (electric), Dad\nretires to home workshop to\nputter with electric power tools.\nThis is a typical day in the life\nof the L.B.E., or Live Better\nElectrically, family. True, not\nevery family has the ready\nmoney to buy major appliances\nwith all cash, or to pay for \"full\nhousepower\" wiring work but\nthis is a problem which low\ncost Appliance Loans and Home\nImprovement Loans from our\nbank have helped many families\nhereabouts to solve. Can wc\nhelp yours be an L.B.E. family?\nr\nIF YOU'RE PROSPERING:\nAre you also progressing; or\nhave you slopped watching\npennies and moved no\nnearer to your \"big\" goals?\nSince you're earning more, why\nnot save more, at our bank?\nSHOES CAN \"WEAR\nDOWN\" from inside as well as\noutside, say footwear experts:\nWashing linings with a sudsy\ncloth helps prolong shoe life.\n\nAROUND THE CLOCK WITH\nTHE LB.E. FAMILY. Electric\nalarm clock rings; Mother\nmakes breakfast\u2014with help of\nelectric coffee-maker, electric\ntoaster. After Dad and chil\ndren depart, Mother speedily\nruns load of laundry in electric\nwasher, dries it in electric drier.\nInafternoon, she whisks through\nroutine housecleaning, with elec\ntric vacuum cleaner; has time\nto read, knit, and \"visit\" as\nsupper steak cooks on electric\ngrill and quick-frozen dessert\ntakes shape in electric refrigera\ntor. Following supper, \"kitchen\npolice\" chore is turned over to\nelectric dishwasher, children\nSidney National Bank\nSIDNEY. MONTANA\nMEMBER FEDERAL DEPOSIT INSURANCE CORPORATION\nJ-K TRUCK LINES\nCUSTOM AND CONTRACT TRUCKING\nWe have L1NCOY RANGE CAKE lor Sale\nFOR FEED OR TRUCKING CALL OR WRITE\nJmhn H. King\nSIDNEY. MONTANA\n20% SAVINGS\no\nOn Most Contracts\nCheck With Us Before\nYou Buy or Renew\nii]\nBroadest Coverage\n;\u00bb\u00bbraww\nat\nWe Write All Forms\nExcept Life\nLowest Rates\n\"n 7\n(Ljabe burner\n\"Your Insurance\nBroker\"\ni\nV\nt\nIt*\n\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0I\nI\nISO\nIBS?\n\u00a3'Nc7f Z?*rur, V 2\nWEE GARAGE I teSB ajgfe*\nTte\nCOMOmOMB\nROOMS\nCOMPLETELY NEW\nIATHS- SHOWERS\nHAWRY K MILES OWNER MANA\u00fcf R\nDon Jensen and family were\nSaturday night visitors at the\nClifford McGinnis home ^to help\nRonda celebrate her eight birth\nday. __\nNOTICE\nOf Moating Of\nMASONIC\nFratornllU\u00ab\n(o)\nG\nMoronic Lode* f*r*\nW eOntrday.\n\u25a0astern Star\nsecond oiid fourth\n\"\u00c2tsemfeli/ fir** nd\nRat\nthird\nfourth\nAttention\nFARMERS\nRANCHERS\nBin T<\nDEAD STOCK\nPieM Wpl\nCall\nSidney Re n de r ing Co.\nPHONE NO. COLLECT\nSidney Moeteae\nR. Zerbe\nRug Cleaning\nCarpets are costly so prolong\ntheir life with patented pro\nfessional cleaning\nSidney's Own\nRUG UPHOLSTERY\nCLEANERS\nSidney\nPhone 1187","height":"22032","width":"16272"}}
